A Stack is a data structure that follows:
LIFO (Last In First Out)
Example:
Push 10
Push 20
Push 30
Stack:
30 <- Top
20
10
Pop()

Stack:
20 <- Top
10
The last element inserted comes out first.
Think of:

Stack of plates
Browser history
Undo operation
Function calls



2. Basic Operations

Operation	Meaning
push(x)	Insert
pop()	Remove top
top()	Access top
empty()	Check empty
size()	Count elements


3. STL Stack in C++
#include <stack>
using namespace std;

stack<int> st;

st.push(10);
st.push(20);
st.push(30);

cout<<st.top();

st.pop();

cout<<st.top();
output:
30
20

4. Time Complexity
Operation	TC
push	O(1)
pop	O(1)
top	O(1)
empty	O(1)


5. When Should You Think About Stack?

This is the most important part.
Whenever you see:

A. Nearest Something
Nearest Greater Left
Nearest Greater Right

Nearest Smaller Left
Nearest Smaller Right
Use Stack.

B. Matching Pairs
()
[] 
{}

Use Stack.

C. Undo Operations
Backspace
Browser history
Undo
Use Stack.

D. Expression Problems
Infix
Prefix
Postfix
Use Stack.

E. Monotonic Problems
Keywords:

Next Greater Element
Previous Greater Element
Stock Span
Histogram
Rainwater

Use Monotonic Stack.

